  <Fragment slot="headline">Salary Calculator Guide: Gross Pay vs Net Pay Explained</Fragment>

  <p>Many people know their salary number but still do not know what will actually hit their bank account every payday.</p>
  <p>That gap exists because <strong>gross pay</strong> and <strong>net pay</strong> are not the same. Gross pay is what you earn before deductions. Net pay is what remains after taxes and withholdings.</p>

  <h2>Gross Pay vs Net Pay</h2>
  <p><strong>Gross pay</strong> is your salary or wages before taxes, insurance, retirement contributions, or other deductions.</p>
  <p><strong>Net pay</strong> is your take-home pay after those deductions are removed.</p>

  <h2>Why Your Take-Home Pay Is Lower Than Your Salary</h2>
  <p>Your paycheck may include deductions for:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Federal income tax</li>
    <li>State income tax, depending on where you live</li>
    <li>Social Security and Medicare</li>
    <li>Health insurance premiums</li>
    <li>401(k) or other retirement contributions</li>
    <li>Other pre-tax or post-tax benefits</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What Usually Makes the Biggest Difference</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Deduction</th>
        <th>What it does</th>
        <th>Why it matters</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Federal income tax</td>
        <td>Applies progressive tax brackets to taxable income</td>
        <td>Usually the largest variable deduction</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>State income tax</td>
        <td>Depends on where you live and work</td>
        <td>Can change your take-home pay meaningfully across states</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>FICA</td>
        <td>Funds Social Security and Medicare</td>
        <td>Shows up on most US paychecks even if income tax is low</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>401(k) and health insurance</td>
        <td>Employer benefits and pre-tax deductions</td>
        <td>Can lower taxable income but reduce current paycheck size</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Pay Frequency Matters</h2>
  <p>Your take-home pay also depends on how often you are paid: weekly, bi-weekly, semi-monthly, or monthly. The annual total may be similar, but the individual paycheck amount will differ.</p>
  <p>This is one reason people misread job offers. A salary might sound strong annually but feel tighter on a per-paycheck basis once tax withholding and benefit deductions are spread across the year.</p>

  <h2>Simple Example</h2>
  <p>If your annual salary is $75,000, your paycheck is not simply $75,000 divided by 12 or 26. Taxes and payroll deductions change the final number, and so does pay frequency.</p>
  <p>That is why a dedicated <a href="https://mycalcstool.com/en/salary-calculator"><strong>Salary Calculator</strong></a> is useful. It gives you a more realistic estimate of annual, monthly, and per-paycheck take-home pay.</p>

  <h2>Pre-Tax vs Post-Tax Deductions</h2>
  <p>Some deductions lower your taxable income before tax is calculated. Others come out after tax. Understanding the difference matters because two jobs with the same gross salary can produce different net pay if benefit structures differ.</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pre-tax deductions</strong> may include 401(k) contributions or health insurance premiums</li>
    <li><strong>Post-tax deductions</strong> may include certain benefit add-ons, wage garnishments, or other employer-specific items</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Common Reasons People Use a Salary Calculator</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Evaluating a new job offer</li>
    <li>Comparing salaries across states</li>
    <li>Estimating monthly budget capacity</li>
    <li>Understanding 401(k) and insurance deductions</li>
    <li>Checking the difference between gross and net income</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Common Mistakes</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Comparing job offers using gross salary only</li>
    <li>Ignoring the tax impact of moving to a different state</li>
    <li>Forgetting pre-tax deductions when setting a monthly budget</li>
    <li>Assuming a monthly paycheck is annual salary divided by 12</li>
  </ul>

  <blockquote>
    <p><strong>Practical rule:</strong> budget with net pay, not gross pay.</p>
    <p><a href="https://mycalcstool.com/en/salary-calculator">Estimate your take-home pay with the salary calculator.</a></p>
  </blockquote>

  <h2>Final Takeaway</h2>
  <p>Your salary number tells only part of the story. The number that matters for budgeting, saving, rent or mortgage planning, and comparing offers is your <strong>net pay after deductions</strong>.</p>
